<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>emsenn.net</title><link>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/order/terms/</link><description>Recent content on emsenn.net</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en-us</language><lastBuildDate>Sun, 29 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/order/terms/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title/><link>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/order/terms/symmetric/</link><pubDate>Sun, 29 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/order/terms/symmetric/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;A &lt;a href="../../sets/terms/binary-relation.md" class="link-internal"&gt;binary relation&lt;/a&gt; R on a &lt;a href="../../sets/terms/set.md" class="link-internal"&gt;set&lt;/a&gt; S is symmetric if the relation goes both ways: for all &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator="true"&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∈&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;S&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;a, b \in S&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, if &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;R&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;a \mathrel{R} b&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; then &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;R&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;b \mathrel{R} a&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. The direction of the pair does not matter. If a is related to b, b is related to a.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Symmetry says: the relation treats both sides equally. Equality is symmetric — if &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;a = b&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; then &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;b = a&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. &amp;ldquo;Is a sibling of&amp;rdquo; is symmetric. &amp;ldquo;Is less than&amp;rdquo; is not: &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mn&gt;3&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;&amp;lt;&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;5&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;3 &amp;lt; 5&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; does not give &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mn&gt;5&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;&amp;lt;&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;3&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;5 &amp;lt; 3&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title/><link>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/order/terms/join/</link><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/order/terms/join/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;The join of two elements a and b in a &lt;a href="./partial-order.md" class="link-internal"&gt;partial order&lt;/a&gt; is their least upper bound: the smallest element c such that &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;a \leq c&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;b \leq c&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Formally, &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∨&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;a \vee b = c&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; requires two conditions: first, c is an upper bound — &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;a \leq c&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;b \leq c&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. Second, c is the least such — for any d with &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;d&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;a \leq d&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;d&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;b \leq d&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, we have &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;d&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;c \leq d&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. The join is unique when it exists, by the same antisymmetry argument as for &lt;a href="./meet.md" class="link-internal"&gt;meet&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title/><link>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/order/terms/lattice/</link><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/order/terms/lattice/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;A lattice is a &lt;a href="./partial-order.md" class="link-internal"&gt;partial order&lt;/a&gt; in which every pair of elements has a &lt;a href="./meet.md" class="link-internal"&gt;meet&lt;/a&gt; (greatest lower bound) and a &lt;a href="./join.md" class="link-internal"&gt;join&lt;/a&gt; (least upper bound).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The meet &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;a \wedge b&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and join &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∨&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;a \vee b&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; give the lattice two binary operations. These operations satisfy four laws: commutativity (&lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;a \wedge b = b \wedge a&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;), associativity (&lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;a \wedge (b \wedge c) = (a \wedge b) \wedge c&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;), idempotence (&lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;a \wedge a = a&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;), and absorption (&lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∨&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;a \wedge (a \vee b) = a&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∨&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;a \vee (a \wedge b) = a&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;). Absorption is the law that ties meet and join together — it says that combining an element with something larger than it (via join) and then taking the meet recovers the original.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title/><link>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/order/terms/meet/</link><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/order/terms/meet/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;The meet of two elements a and b in a &lt;a href="./partial-order.md" class="link-internal"&gt;partial order&lt;/a&gt; is their greatest lower bound: the largest element c such that &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;c \leq a&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;c \leq b&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Formally, &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;a \wedge b = c&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; requires two conditions: first, c is a lower bound — &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;c \leq a&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;c \leq b&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. Second, c is the greatest such — for any d with &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;d&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;d \leq a&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;d&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;d \leq b&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, we have &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;d&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;d \leq c&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. The meet is unique when it exists, because if two elements are both greatest lower bounds, antisymmetry forces them to be equal.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title/><link>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/order/terms/preorder/</link><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/order/terms/preorder/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;A preorder on a &lt;a href="../sets/terms/set.md" class="link-internal"&gt;set&lt;/a&gt; S is a &lt;a href="../sets/terms/binary-relation.md" class="link-internal"&gt;binary relation&lt;/a&gt; &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;\leq&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; that is &lt;a href="./reflexive.md" class="link-internal"&gt;reflexive&lt;/a&gt; (&lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;a \leq a&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; for all a) and &lt;a href="./transitive.md" class="link-internal"&gt;transitive&lt;/a&gt; (&lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;a \leq b&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;b \leq c&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; imply &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;a \leq c&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A preorder is the weakest structure that supports a notion of &amp;ldquo;at least as much as.&amp;rdquo; It allows ties: elements a and b can satisfy both &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;a \leq b&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;b \leq a&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; without being equal. When ties are ruled out by adding &lt;a href="./antisymmetric.md" class="link-internal"&gt;antisymmetry&lt;/a&gt;, the preorder becomes a &lt;a href="./partial-order.md" class="link-internal"&gt;partial order&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Antisymmetric</title><link>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/order/terms/antisymmetric/</link><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/order/terms/antisymmetric/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;A relation R on a set S is antisymmetric if mutual relatedness implies equality: whenever aRb and bRa, then a = b.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Antisymmetry is what distinguishes a &lt;a href="./partial-order.md" class="link-internal"&gt;partial order&lt;/a&gt; from a &lt;a href="./preorder.md" class="link-internal"&gt;preorder&lt;/a&gt;. A preorder allows &amp;ldquo;ties&amp;rdquo; where a ≤ b and b ≤ a without a = b (the elements are equivalent but not identical). A &lt;a href="./partial-order.md" class="link-internal"&gt;partial order&lt;/a&gt; rules this out: the only way for two elements to be mutually related is for them to be the same element.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Partial Order</title><link>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/order/terms/partial-order/</link><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/order/terms/partial-order/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;A partial order on a set is a relation ≤ that satisfies three rules. It is &lt;a href="./reflexive.md" class="link-internal"&gt;reflexive&lt;/a&gt;: everything is ≤ itself. It is &lt;a href="./transitive.md" class="link-internal"&gt;transitive&lt;/a&gt;: if a ≤ b and b ≤ c, then a ≤ c. It is &lt;a href="./antisymmetric.md" class="link-internal"&gt;antisymmetric&lt;/a&gt;: if a ≤ b and b ≤ a, then a and b are the same thing. A set with a partial order on it is called a partially ordered set, or poset.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Partial&amp;rdquo; means not everything has to be comparable. Two elements can just have no relation to each other — neither one is ≤ the other. This is what separates a partial order from a total order, where every pair must be comparable. Numbers with ≤ are a total order. Sets with ⊆ are a partial order — {1,2} and {2,3} are not comparable because neither contains the other.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Reflexive</title><link>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/order/terms/reflexive/</link><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/order/terms/reflexive/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;A relation R on a set S is reflexive if every element is related to itself: for all a ∈ S, aRa holds.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Reflexivity is one of the three defining properties of a &lt;a href="./partial-order.md" class="link-internal"&gt;partial order&lt;/a&gt; (along with &lt;a href="./transitive.md" class="link-internal"&gt;transitivity&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="./antisymmetric.md" class="link-internal"&gt;antisymmetry&lt;/a&gt;) and one of the two defining properties of a &lt;a href="./preorder.md" class="link-internal"&gt;preorder&lt;/a&gt; (along with transitivity).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Reflexivity says: every element is at least as good as itself, every point is accessible from itself, every object has an identity &lt;a href="../../categories/ordinary-categories/terms/morphism.md" class="link-internal"&gt;morphism&lt;/a&gt;. In a poset viewed as a &lt;a href="../../categories/ordinary-categories/terms/category.md" class="link-internal"&gt;category&lt;/a&gt;, reflexivity corresponds to the existence of &lt;a href="../../categories/ordinary-categories/terms/identity-morphism.md" class="link-internal"&gt;identity morphisms&lt;/a&gt;: the &lt;a href="../../categories/ordinary-categories/terms/morphism.md" class="link-internal"&gt;morphism&lt;/a&gt; a → a witnesses that a ≤ a.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Transitive</title><link>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/order/terms/transitive/</link><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/order/terms/transitive/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;A relation R on a set S is transitive if it chains: whenever aRb and bRc, then aRc.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Transitivity is one of the three defining properties of a &lt;a href="./partial-order.md" class="link-internal"&gt;partial order&lt;/a&gt; and one of the two defining properties of a &lt;a href="./preorder.md" class="link-internal"&gt;preorder&lt;/a&gt;. It captures the idea that the relation is coherent across intermediate steps — if a ≤ b and b ≤ c, then a ≤ c directly, without needing b as a witness.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>